{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Aimaq Hazara | image = | caption = | population = 169,030 <ref name=worldmap>{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldmap.org/getprofile.php?ROG3=AF&QryFld=CP_Peoplegroup |title=Worldmap.org |access-date=2013-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226091523/http://www.worldmap.org/getprofile.php?ROG3=AF&QryFld=CP_Peoplegroup |archive-date=2013-12-26 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> | languages = [[Dari language|Dari]] <ref name=worldmap/> | religions = [[Sunni Islam]] | related = [[Hazaras]], [[Aimaqs]] }}
The '''Aimaq Hazaras''' (Hazara-e-kala-e-nau, Hazara-e-qala-e-naw, Sunni Hazara) are the [[Aimaq people|Aimaq]]'s subtribe of [[Hazara people|Hazara]] origin, however they are [[Sunni Muslim]]s and other Hazaras are [[Shia Muslim]]s. The Aimaq Hazara consists of 38 subtribes.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.uscwm.info/op1040/pdfs/144.pdf |title=Aimaq |author=anonymous |date=n.d. |access-date=2013-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229110139/http://www.uscwm.info/op1040/pdfs/144.pdf |archive-date=2013-12-29 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> The Aimaq Hazara and [[Taimuri]] peoples are the most [[Mongoloid]] of the Aimaqs. The Aimaq people live in traditional Afghan black tents but the Aimaq Hazara and [[Taimuri]] are semi-nomadic who live in [[yurt]]s covered with [[felt]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.tribalanalysiscenter.com/PDF-External/Hazara%20Baluchistan.pdf |author=Muhammad Owtadoiajam |year=1976 |title=A Sociological Study Of The Hazara Tribe In Baluchistan (An Analysis Of Socio-Cultural Change)}}</ref>
