'''Joseph Baly''' (1824 &ndash; 1909)<ref>Satoshi Mizutani: "The Meaning of White: Race, Class, and the 'Domiciled Community' in British India 1858-1930", [[Oxford]], [[Oxford University Press|OUP]], 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-19-969770-0}}, p.121</ref> was [[Archdeacon of Calcutta]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/d76b7cdc-1780-4023-85b8-a02981ccb5e5 | title= BALY (Joseph), Archdeacon of Calcutta | publisher=National Archives | accessdate=28 November 2018 }}</ref> from 1872<ref>'Ecclesiastical Intelligence' [[Essex Standard]] (Colchester, England), Friday, 26 April 1872; Issue 2158</ref> until 1883;<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]], London, Horace Cox, 1908, p. 66</ref>

Baly was educated at [[Worcester College, Oxford]],<ref>{{alox2|title=Baly, Joseph}}</ref> graduating [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1846<ref>''University Intelligence'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Monday, 1 Jun 1846; pg. 3; Issue 19251</ref> and [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|M.A.]] in 1857.<ref>'UNIVERSITY INTELLIGENCE' [[The Morning Post]] (London, England), Monday, 13 July 1857; pg. 6; Issue 26063</ref> He was [[ordained]] [[deacon]] in 1847<ref>'GENERAL ORDINATIONS' [[The Morning Post]] (London, England), Wednesday, 22 December 1847; pg. 1; Issue 23101</ref> and [[priest]] in 1848.<ref>'GENERAL ORDINATIONS' [[The Morning Post]] (London, England), Monday, 1 January 1849; pg. 7; Issue 23422</ref> He served [[Curate|curacies]] in [[Leicester]] and [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]].<ref>'Testimonial to the Rev Joseph Baly, B.A' [[Royal Cornwall Gazette]] (Truro, England), Friday, 7 July 1854; pg. 8; Issue 2663</ref> In 1854 he became [[Warden (college)|Warden]] of [[S. Thomas' College, Mount Lavinia|St Thomas's College, Colombo]].<ref>[http://www.stcmount.edu.lk/wardens-of-s-thomas-college.html College web-site] {{deadlink|date=November 2018}}</ref> He later served as [[Chaplain]] at [[Allahabad]], [[Sealkote]]  and [[Simla]] before returning to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]] as its [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|Rector]] (1870<ref>'CORNWALL' [[Royal Cornwall Gazette]] (Truro, England), Saturday, 4 June 1870; pg. ROYAL CORNWALL GAZETTE, SATURDAY MORNING, JUNE 4, 1870.; Issue 3490</ref>–1872).<ref>''Ecclesiastical Intelligence'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Saturday, 4 Jun 1870; pg. 7; Issue 26768</ref> He was appointed a [[List of University of Calcutta people|Fellow of the University of Calcutta]] in 1879. On his return from [[India]] he was  [[Chaplain]] of [[Windsor Great Park]] from 1885<ref>[http://forebears.co.uk/england/berkshire/old-windsor Forbears]</ref> until 1906.<ref>''Court Circular.'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Saturday, 29 Dec 1906; pg. 10; Issue 38216</ref>

He died on 6 November 1909.<ref>''The Rev. Joseph Baly'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Tuesday, 9 Nov 1909; pg. 11; Issue 39112</ref>

His daughter Amelia Baly was the wife of Field Marshal [[George White (British Army officer)|Sir George White]].

