'''Scott Ramon Seguro Mescudi''' (born January 30, 1984),<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:wcfqxzu5ldte~T1|title=Kid Cudi > Biography|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|year=2009|publisher=allmusic|accessdate=May 22, 2009}}</ref> better known by his [[stage name]] '''Kid Cudi''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|ʌ|d|i}}; often stylized as '''KiD CuDi'''), is an American singer, rapper, songwriter, record producer and actor from [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]]. 

Cudi first gained major recognition following the release of his first official full-length project, a [[mixtape]] titled ''A Kid Named Cudi'' (2008). The mixtape caught the attention of American rapper-producer [[Kanye West]], who subsequently signed Cudi to his [[GOOD Music]] label imprint in late 2008. In 2008 his debut single "[[Day 'n' Nite]]" led him to prominence, reaching the top five of the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts. Cudi's debut album ''[[Man on the Moon: The End of Day]]'' (2009) was later [[Music recording sales certification|certified two-times platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=kid+cudi+man+on+the+moon#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|work=RIAA|access-date=August 2, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2010, he released ''[[Man on the Moon II: The Legend of Mr. Rager]]'', which was preceded by "[[Erase Me (song)|Erase Me]]" and "[[Mr. Rager]]". Later that year Cudi formed a [[rock band]], now known as [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]], with his long-time collaborator [[Dot da Genius]], releasing one [[WZRD (album)|eponymous debut album]] in early 2012. The album debuted at number one on the [[Rock Albums|Top Rock Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/kid-cudi-ditches-rap-for-rock_1178078 |title=Kid Cudi Ditches Rap For Rock |publisher=Contactmusic.com |date=October 31, 2010 |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://keepittrill.com/online/2010/10/kid-cudi-forms-rock-band-called-wizard/ |title=Kid Cudi Forms New Rock Band Called 'Wizard' |publisher=Keepittrill.com |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref> In April 2013, Cudi released ''[[Indicud]]'', which became his highest-charting album on multiple charts. In February 2014, Cudi unexpectedly released his fourth album, ''[[Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon]]'', exclusively to digital retailers with no promotion. In 2015 Cudi released his rock album ''[[Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven]]'' to negative reception. In 2016 he returned to hip-hop with his sixth album ''[[Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin']]'' to generally positive reviews. Cudi later released a joint album with West under the [[Kids See Ghosts|eponymous name]] ''[[Kids See Ghosts (album)|Kids See Ghosts]]''. The album was met with critical acclaim. 

As of 2018, Cudi has released six [[studio album]]s as a solo artist and has sold over 5.2 million digital singles and has worked with numerous prominent artists in the music industry, including [[Jay Z]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[David Guetta]], [[MGMT]], [[Shakira]], [[Snoop Dogg]] and [[Michael Bolton]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolgamott|first=Kent|title=What You Need to Know About Kid Cudi|url=http://journalstar.com/entertainment/music/article_f5e55616-abe0-5b71-b2d6-61a138c22929.html|publisher=JournalStar.com|accessdate=July 7, 2011|date=July 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2012/08/05/man-on-the-moon-ii-the-legend-of-mr-rager-certified-gold/ |title=Man on the Moon II: The Legend Of Mr. Rager Certified Gold &#124; Dat New 'Cudi' |publisher=Datnewcudi.com |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325030433/http://datnewcudi.com/2012/08/05/man-on-the-moon-ii-the-legend-of-mr-rager-certified-gold/ |archivedate=March 25, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=232254629059129344|date=August 5, 2012|title=Man on the Moon II The Legend Of Mr Rager is certified gold.  Which means, I have 2 gold albums and over 5.2 million digital singles sold}}</ref> With his originality and creativity, as well as the emotion he conveys in his music, Cudi has amassed a large [[Cult following|cult-like following]] among high school students, college students and [[Stoner (drug user)|stoners]] alike.<ref>{{cite web|author=Insanul Ahmed|title=The 50 Best Debut Rap Singles|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/the-50-best-debut-rap-singles/kid-cudi-day-n-nite|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=March 20, 2013|date=March 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alex Stone|title=Kid Cudi Feels Mixtape Releases Are A Waste Of Time|url=http://theversed.com/2012/03/29/kid-cudi-feels-mixtape-releases-are-a-waste-of-time/|publisher=TheVersed|accessdate=March 20, 2013|date=March 29, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404213025/http://theversed.com/2012/03/29/kid-cudi-feels-mixtape-releases-are-a-waste-of-time/|archivedate=April 4, 2013|df=}}</ref> After signing to GOOD Music, Cudi has since gone on to launch his own record label imprints, the now-dissolved Dream On and current independent label Wicked Awesome Records.<ref name="dreamon">{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/02/27/kid-cudi-splits-with-manager-launching-new-label/|title=Kid Cudi Splits With Manager, Launching New Label|date=February 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110120006/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/02/27/kid-cudi-splits-with-manager-launching-new-label/|archivedate=January 10, 2012|deadurl=yes|accessdate=October 17, 2011|df=}}</ref><ref name="dreamon" /><ref name="wicked awesome">{{cite web|url=http://datnewcudi.com/2011/04/22/kid-cudi-announces-new-label-band-name/|title=Kid Cudi Announces New Label & Band Name|date=April 22, 2011|publisher=Datnewcudi.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427020801/http://datnewcudi.com/2011/04/22/kid-cudi-announces-new-label-band-name/|archivedate=April 27, 2012|deadurl=yes|accessdate=October 11, 2012|df=}}</ref> In 2010, Cudi ventured into acting when he began starring in the [[HBO]] series ''[[How to Make It in America]]''. Cudi has since appeared in several feature films, including ''[[Goodbye World]]'', ''[[Need for Speed (film)|Need for Speed]]'' and ''[[Entourage (film)|Entourage]]''. In addition, he has made appearances on television shows such as ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'', ''[[The Cleveland Show]]'' and ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]''. In 2015, he was the bandleader on the [[IFC (U.S. TV network)|IFC]] series,  [[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|''Comedy Bang! Bang!'']].

== Early life ==
Scott Ramon Seguro Mescudi was born on January 30, 1984, in [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], and grew up in [[Shaker Heights]] and [[Solon, Ohio|Solon]].<ref name="spin">{{cite web|author=Fennessey, Sean |url=http://www.spin.com/2010/09/kid-cudi-how-he-made-it-america/ |title=Kid Cudi: How He Made It in America |work=Spin.com |publisher=[[Spin Media]] |date=September 14, 2010 |accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref> He is the youngest of four children, with two brothers, Domingo and Dean, and a sister, Maisha.<ref name=Soeder/> His mother, Elsie Harriet (Banks), is a middle-school choir teacher at Roxboro Middle School in [[Cleveland Heights, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Nabil Elderkin |url=http://www.cleveland.com/popmusic/index.ssf/2009/06/before_he_became_the_most_buzz.html |title=Before he became the most buzzed-about rookie in the music business, Kid Cudi was a kid from Cleveland with big dreams |publisher=cleveland.com |date= |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://birth-records.mooseroots.com/l/12241322/Scott-Raymon-Seguro-Mescudi|title=Scott Raymon Seguro Mescudi (b. 1984)|author=|date=|work=mooseroots.com}}</ref> His father, Lindberg Styles Mescudi, was a house painter, substitute teacher and [[World War II]] [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] veteran. His father was of African-American and Mexican-American descent, while his mother is African-American.<ref name=Soul/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/X43H-G1D |title=Person Details for Lindbergh Mescudi in household of Charles Mescudi, "United States Census, 1930" — |publisher=Familysearch.org |date= |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name="MTV Newsroom">{{cite news|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/03/10/kid-cudis-not-so-dark-alter-ego-revealed/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104050448/http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/03/10/kid-cudis-not-so-dark-alter-ego-revealed/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=January 4, 2013|title=Kid Cudi's Not-So-Dark Alter Ego Revealed!|last=Smith|first=Angelique|date=March 10, 2009|work=MTV Newsroom|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=September 13, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/X43H-G1D|title=Person Details for Lindbergh Mescudi in household of Charles Mescudi, "United States Census, 1930" — FamilySearch.org|author=|date=|work=familysearch.org}}</ref>

When he was eleven years old, Cudi's father died of cancer; his passing had a significant effect on Cudi's personality and subsequently his music.<ref name=Soul>{{Cite journal |last=Hoard |first=Christian |date=September 17, 2009 |title=Kid Cudi: Hip-Hop's Sensitive Soul |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2009/09/14/rolling-stone-kid-cudi-hip-hops-sensitive-soul/ |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |volume= |issue=1087 |page=40 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204224314/http://datnewcudi.com/2009/09/14/rolling-stone-kid-cudi-hip-hops-sensitive-soul/ |archivedate=February 4, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Cudi attended [[Shaker Heights High School]] for two years before transferring to [[Solon High School]]. He was expelled from the school for threatening to punch his principal and would later earn his [[GED]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/25-things-you-didnt-know-about-kid-cudi/expelled-from-high-school |title=He got expelled from high school for threatening to punch his principal. — 25 Things You Didn't Know About Kid Cudi |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref> Cudi studied film at the [[University of Toledo]], dropping out after a year.<ref name=Soeder>{{cite news |first=John |last=Soeder |title=Before he became the most buzzed-about rookie in the music business, Kid Cudi was a kid from Cleveland with big dreams |url=http://www.cleveland.com/music/index.ssf/2009/06/before_he_became_the_most_buzz.html |work=[[The Plain Dealer]] |date=June 27, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yeiitIX3?url=http://www.cleveland.com/popmusic/index.ssf/2009/06/before_he_became_the_most_buzz.html|archivedate=May 13, 2011 }}</ref> His subsequent plan to join the [[U.S. Navy]] didn't pan out because of his juvenile police record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/25-things-you-didnt-know-about-kid-cudi/navy |title=After dropping out of college, he was determined to join the Navy but was denied due to his juvenile police record. — 25 Things You Didn't Know About Kid Cudi |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref>

== Musical career ==

=== 2003–08: Beginnings in New York ===
Cudi first began rapping towards the end of his high school career, inspired by [[alternative hip hop]] groups such as [[The Pharcyde]] and [[A Tribe Called Quest]].<ref name=Soul/> He moved to [[New York City]] to pursue a music career.<ref name="allmusic"/> Upon his arrival, he stayed with his uncle, Kalil Madi:<ref name="2009interview">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2009/07/kid-cudi/page/2 |title=Kid Cudi |publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=August 3, 2009 |accessdate=March 16, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427174922/http://www.complex.com/music/2009/07/kid-cudi/page/2 |archivedate=April 27, 2013 }}</ref>

{{cquote|I was working at this restaurant in Cleveland. There was this white dude in his 40s who was cool as shit and would tell me, "You're funny and people like you. You need to move the fuck out of Ohio and just do this." My uncle told me I could come out there and stay with him in the [[South Bronx]] until I got on my feet. I'd never met him; this was my father's older brother, the last of my father's siblings, so I wanted to make that connection anyway. I moved in 2004 with my little [[Demo (music)|demo]] and maybe $500.<ref name="q&a">{{cite web|author= |url=http://musicconnection.com/qa-kid-cudi/ |title=Q&A With Kid Cudi |publisher=Musicconnection.com |date=November 4, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>}}

Shortly after he moved from Cleveland, a [[A Bathing Ape|BAPE]] store opened up in the city, where he later applied for a job:<ref name="bape">{{cite web|url=http://hypebeast.com/2010/3/bathing-ape-kid-cudi-interview-photoshoot?_locale=en |title=A Bathing Ape x Kid Cudi Interview & Photoshoot |publisher=HypeBeast |date=March 29, 2010 |accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref>

{{cquote|I discovered what BAPE was when I moved to NY, the store opened up shortly after I moved from Cleveland. I was always a fan of the brand but it just wasn't something I could afford back then. I remember working there my first couple of weeks in the same uniform cause I didn’t own anything prior to being hired. So it was a dream come true to be able to work at the store I dreamed of shopping in one day. Over a couple of years I might have applied at the store 3 or 4 times before the last attempt that got me hired. I fell in love with BAPE because of their color selection and artwork. I love the style of their cartoons.}}

While working there Cudi met future mentor [[Kanye West]], for the first time after forgetting to remove an anti-theft device from a jacket West had purchased.<ref name="bape"/> His uncle later kicked him out, leading to his writing "[[Day 'n' Nite]]":

{{cquote|My uncle that I lived with passed in 2006. We were actually beefing because he forced me out the house when I didn't have another situation set up, so I was bitter. I never apologized for it, and that kills me. That's why I wrote "Day 'n' Nite". If he wasn't there to let me stay with him those first few months, there would be no Kid Cudi. It fucked me up watching him go, but it was like, "I have to fulfill this destiny now for sure." Things were moving but they weren't solidified yet. I had "Day 'n' Nite", we were just getting started, and I was like, "This shit has got to pop off." I wasn't taking no for an answer.<ref name="2009interview"/>}}

[[File:Kid Cudi Summerstage Central Park.jpg|thumb|left|Kid Cudi performing at Central Park [[Summerstage]] in New York City, in 2008.]]
Cudi's early work caught the attention of Kanye West, whose then-manager [[Plain Pat]], had introduced Cudi's music to him, subsequently leading West to sign Cudi to his [[GOOD Music]] imprint later that year. In July 2008, Kid Cudi released his first mixtape, ''[[A Kid Named Cudi]]'' (executive produced by Plain Pat and [[Emile Haynie]]), in collaboration with New York street-wear brand 10.Deep as a free download.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://illroots.com/2008/07/17/kid-cuDi-a-kid-named-cuDi/ |title=10.Deep Presents: Kid Cudi – "A Kid Named Cudi Mixtape" |publisher=Illroots.com |date=July 17, 2008 |accessdate=October 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424231047/http://illroots.com/2008/07/17/kid-cuDi-a-kid-named-cuDi/ |archivedate=April 24, 2012 |df= }}</ref>

Kanye West first called upon Cudi to reference [[Refrain|hooks]] for American rapper and mogul [[Jay-Z]], and while in the studio Cudi and West went from working on ''[[The Blueprint 3]]'' (2009) to West's [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]-esque ''[[808s & Heartbreak]]'' (2008).<ref name="2009interview"/> Cudi’s assistance on the latter includes co-writing credits and or vocals on "[[Heartless (Kanye West song)|Heartless]]," "[[Welcome to Heartbreak]]," "[[Paranoid (Kanye West song)|Paranoid]]" and "RoboCop."<ref name="2009interview"/> Kid Cudi was a prominent [[songwriter]] and featured artist on ''808s & Heartbreak'', with "Paranoid" and "Heartless" being released as singles, while "Welcome to Heartbreak" charted as an album cut and peaked at number 87 on the [[Pop 100]].<ref name="Pop100">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=kid cudi|chart=Pop 100}}|title=Billboard Pop 100 Chart Positions|publisher=''Billboard''|accessdate=January 9, 2009}}</ref>

Kid Cudi's first television appearance was at the 2008 [[MTV Video Music Awards]], alongside [[Travis Barker]] and [[Adam Goldstein|DJ AM]]. Cudi was promoted as an artist to watch for in media such as ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'', ''[[Source (magazine)|The Source]]'', ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' and [[BBC News]]'s 2009 [[Sound of... (BBC poll)|Sound of]] poll.<ref>{{cite news |title = BBC Sound of 2008: The longlist |publisher = BBC News |date = December 5, 2008 |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7758169.stm |accessdate = January 1, 2009}}</ref> [[MTV News]] reported on Cudi on a series of reports ''MCs To Watch In 2009''.<ref name="MCs to watch">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1602354/20090108/kid_cudi.jhtml|title=Kid Cudi|last=Roberts|first=Steven|date=January 8, 2009|work=MCs To Watch In 2009|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=August 28, 2009}}</ref>

=== 2009–10: ''Man on the Moon'' series ===
{{Main article|Man on the Moon: The End of Day|Man on the Moon II: The Legend of Mr. Rager}}
[[File:Kid Cudi Moon2.jpg|thumb|Kid Cudi performing on August 6, 2009.]]
In late 2008, Cudi was revealed to be included in [[XXL (magazine)|''XXL'']]'s 2009 annual Freshman Class. He was featured on the cover alongside fellow up-and-coming rappers [[Asher Roth]], [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]], [[B.o.B]], [[Charles Hamilton (rapper)|Charles Hamilton]], [[Cory Gunz]], [[Blu (rapper)|Blu]], [[Mickey Factz]], [[Ace Hood]] and [[Curren$y]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://highbridnation.com/2008/10/21/first-look-xxl-freshman-class-of-09-covers/ | title=First Look: XXL Freshman Class of ’09 Covers | publisher= | work=''highbridnation.com'' | date=October 21, 2008 | accessdate=March 13, 2013 | author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hiphoppress.com/2008/10/xxls-class-of-0 | title=XXL’s Class of ’09 Cover: Top 10 Freshmen | publisher= | work=''hiphoppress.com'' | date=October 20, 2008 | accessdate=March 13, 2013 | author= | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130411022602/http://www.hiphoppress.com/2008/10/xxls-class-of-0 | archivedate=April 11, 2013 | df= }}</ref> On February 17, 2009, he appeared on [[Snoop Dogg]]'s MTV talk show ''[[Dogg After Dark]]'', performing "Day 'n' Nite" at the end of the show. Two days later on February 19, 2009, Cudi appeared on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s ''[[106 & Park]]'', alongside [[Kanye West]] to debut the music video of "Day 'n' Nite". On February 25, 2009, Cudi [[Internet leak|self-leaked]] a [[teaser trailer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videos.onsmash.com/v/v7nQrrBTj4nqfxCK |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 21, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228095744/http://videos.onsmash.com/v/v7nQrrBTj4nqfxCK |archivedate=February 28, 2009 |df= }} </ref> for the upcoming ''[[Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen]]'' film, using his song "Sky Might Fall" in the background; later he posted that he made the trailer himself and was in talks to possibly making it official.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1606279/story.jhtml |title = Kid Cudi Has 'Eureka' Moment With 'Transformers' Trailer  |accessdate = April 2, 2009 |last= Roberts|first=Steven|date = March 4, 2009 |publisher = [[MTV News]] }}</ref>

In February 2009, Kid Cudi also made a [[cameo appearance]] next to [[Solange Knowles|Solange]], in the video for her song "[[T.O.N.Y.]]". On March 16, 2009, Kid Cudi performed on [[mtvU]]'s Spring Break special, and the following day he performed three songs on NBC's ''[[Last Call with Carson Daly]]''. Cudi teamed up with partner and record producer Emile Haynie, to produce an exclusive single titled "Switchin Lanes", for the video game ''[[Midnight Club: Los Angeles]]'', part of its "South Central Premium Upgrade" [[Downloadable content|downloadable content (DLC)]], which came out March 19, 2009, for the [[PlayStation 3]] and March 27, 2009, for the [[Xbox 360]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.rockstargames.com/midnightclubLA/southcentral/ |title = Midnight Club: Los Angeles South Central DLC Kid Cudi Exclusive |publisher = [[Rockstar Games]]|accessdate=April 20, 2013 }}</ref> He has also appeared as a musical guest on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' and ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''. In June 2009, he made a cameo in [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' video for "[[I Gotta Feeling]]", alongside [[David Guetta]], where the two met for the first time and subsequently recorded their international hit "[[Memories (David Guetta song)|Memories]]". In 2009, he had also been on two magazine covers, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' (August/September 2009) and ''[[URB (magazine)|URB]]'' (August 2009).

[[File:Kid Cudi MOTM Performance.jpg|thumb|left|Kid Cudi performing in September 2009.]]
He revealed information about his future plans via his blog, saying that a possible collaborative album with [[Chip tha Ripper]] could be followed with a collaborative project with [[electronic rock]] duo [[Ratatat]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Kid Cudi|title=Features|url=http://www.kidcudi.com/news/?p=688|date=May 2, 2009|accessdate=August 28, 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507183413/http://www.kidcudi.com/news/?p=688|archivedate=May 7, 2009|df=}}</ref> On May 5, 2009  Iranian-American progressive house DJ [[Sharam]], released "She Came Along", the [[lead single]] from his debut studio album, ''[[Get Wild (album)|Get Wild]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web | title=She Came Along (feat. Kid Cudi) by Sharam | url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/she-came-along-feat.-kid-cudi/id314247463 | work=[[iTunes Store]] | publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] | accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref> The song, featuring Cudi, charted for 15 weeks on the Bulgaria Singles Top 40. It entered the chart on position 40 on week 30/2009, and its last appearance was on week 44/2009. It peaked at number 11, where it stayed for 1 week.<ref>{{cite web | title=Sharam and Kid Cudi - She Came Along - Music Charts| url=http://acharts.us/song/45498 | work=''αCharts.us'' | publisher= | accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref>

During the summer of 2009, Cudi joined fellow up-and-coming rappers [[Asher Roth]] and [[B.o.B]], for 'The Great Hangover' [[concert tour]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616466/20090717/kid_cudi.jhtml|title=Kid Cudi, Asher Roth Want Hangover Tour To Be A 'Movement'|last=Roberts|first=Steven|date=July 17, 2009|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=August 28, 2009|format=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1613186/asher-roth-kid-cudi-hitting-road-together.jhtml|title=Asher Roth And Kid Cudi Hitting The Road For Great Hangover Tour|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=June 3, 2009|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=March 15, 2013|format=mdy}}</ref>
In late 2009, Kid Cudi was featured on the highly anticipated [[Jay-Z]] album ''[[The Blueprint 3]]'', on the song "Already Home".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/36262-jay-zs-iblueprint-3i-the-tracklist/|title=Blueprint 3 Track-List|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=August 19, 2009|format=mdy}}</ref> On September 14, 2009, [[BET]] premiered their ''Rising Icons'' profile of Kid Cudi. During the 30 minute show Cudi performed "CuDi Zone", "Mr. Solo Dolo", "Day ‘n’ Nite" and "Make Her Say". Cudi also discussed his childhood, his move to New York to begin his career as an artist and more.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/grey-goose-entertainment-and-bet-present-rising-icons/ |title=Grey Goose Entertainment and BET Present: Rising Icons - Show News, Reviews, Recaps and Photos |website=TV.com |date= |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nahright.com/2009/09/15/video-bet-rising-icon-kid-cudi/ |title=Video: BET Rising Icon: KiD CuDi |publisher=Nah Right |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.luxuriousprototype.com/events/bet-rising-icons-w-melanie-fiona-and-kid-cudi/ |title=BET Rising Icons w/ Melanie Fiona and Kid Cudi. |publisher=LuxuriousPROTOTYPE |date=August 22, 2009 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebritybug.net/2009/09/rising-icons-kid-cudi.html |title=Rising Icons: Kid Cudi |publisher=Celebrity Bug |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>

Cudi's debut album ''[[Man on the Moon: The End of Day]]'', was released on [[Universal Motown]] Records on September 15, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://internetpopular.wordpress.com/2009/09/15/kid-cudi-man-on-the-moon-released/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120728173608/http://internetpopular.wordpress.com/2009/09/15/kid-cudi-man-on-the-moon-released/|deadurl=yes|title=WordPress.com|date=July 28, 2012|archivedate=July 28, 2012|publisher=}}</ref> and sold 104,419 copies in the first week and charted at #4.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.shabooty.com/2009/09/23/jay-z-tops-album-sales-two-weeks-in-a-row-sells-298k.php |title=Jay-Z Tops Album Sales Two Weeks In A Row |publisher=Shabooty.com |date=September 23, 2009 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> The album's [[lead single]] "Day 'n' Nite", Kid Cudi's greatest commercial success thus far, charted well in both the U.S. and in Europe. The second [[Single (music)|single]] released was "[[Make Her Say]]" (originally titled "I Poke Her Face"), which features a sample from [[Lady Gaga]]'s hit single "[[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]]" and performances by Kanye West and [[Common (rapper)|Common]]. Common was also featured throughout the album, as the narrator.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1612265/20090527/west_kanye.jhtml|title=Kanye West 'Inspired' By Lady Gaga's 'Face' For Kid Cudi Single|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=May 27, 2009|work=Mixtape Daily|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=August 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616551/20090720/kid_cudi.jhtml|title=Kanye West, Common Lend Kid Cudi Bicoastal Support In Video|last=Roberts|first=Steven|date=July 20, 2009|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=August 28, 2009}}</ref>

In September 2009, Cudi co-headlined [[50 Cent]]'s "50 Fest" concert, along with fellow American rapper [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopwired.com/2009/09/09/50-cent-recruits-wale-kid-cudi-and-corey-gunz-for-%E2%80%9C50-fest%E2%80%9D/ |title=50 Cent Recruits Wale, Kid Cudi and Corey Gunz for "50 Fest" |publisher=Hip-Hop Wired |date=September 9, 2009 |accessdate=August 9, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008150158/http://hiphopwired.com/2009/09/09/50-cent-recruits-wale-kid-cudi-and-corey-gunz-for-%e2%80%9c50-fest%e2%80%9d/ |archive-date=October 8, 2016 |dead-url=yes  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AYwm4snUmo |title=Thisis50 Fest - Focus On Kid Cudi &#124; Behind The Scenes &#124; 50 Cent |publisher=YouTube |date=October 6, 2009 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1622984/50-cent-unites-nyc-hip-hop-at-thisis50-festival/ |title=50 Cent Unites NYC Hip-Hop At ThisIs50 Festival |publisher=MTV |date=October 4, 2009 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> In a late 2009 interview, Cudi announced that the follow-up to his debut album would be a [[compilation album]] entitled ''Cudder and the Revolution of Evolution'', which would have many collaborations. He stated he had already recorded songs with [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Travis Barker]], [[Clipse]], [[Cage (rapper)|Cage]] and [[Pharrell Williams|Pharrell]], and would also like to work with [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]], [[Green Day]], [[Kings of Leon]], [[Robin Thicke]], [[The Killers]] and [[The Postal Service]] on the album. It was also rumored that ''Man on the Moon: The End of Day'' would be followed up by a sequel titled ''Man on the Moon: The Ghost in the Machine'' and that the ''Man on the Moon'' series would be a trilogy.<ref>[http://datnewcudi.com/2009/08/25/kid-cudi-interview-with-honey-magazine/ Kid Cudi Interview with Honey Magazine – Dat New 'Cudi'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091030210710/http://datnewcudi.com/2009/08/25/kid-cudi-interview-with-honey-magazine/ |date=October 30, 2009 }}. Datnewcudi.com (August 25, 2009). Retrieved on April 26, 2011.</ref> Kid Cudi was nominated for three [[2010 Grammy Awards]], for his singles "Day 'n' Nite" and "Make Her Say".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2009/12/02/kid-cudi-recieves-three-2010-grammy-nominations/ |title=Kid Cudi receives Three Grammy Nominations |publisher=Datnewcudi.com |date= |accessdate=October 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427061846/http://datnewcudi.com/2009/12/02/kid-cudi-recieves-three-2010-grammy-nominations/ |archivedate=April 27, 2012 |df= }}</ref>
[[File:Kid Cudi 2010 1.jpg|Kid Cudi in New York City on April 4, 2010|thumb]]
In January 2010, Cudi released ''Man on the Moon: The End of Day''{{'}}s third and final single "[[Pursuit of Happiness (song)|Pursuit of Happiness]]", which was eventually certified platinum by the RIAA. In 2010, Kid Cudi was featured on Snoop Dogg's re-release of ''Malice n Wonderland'', titled ''[[More Malice]]'', on the lead single "[[That Tree]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2010/01/20/kid-cudi-featured-on-snoop-doggs-more-malice/ |title=Kid Cudi Featured on Snoop Dogg’s "More Malice" |publisher=Datnewcudi.com |date= |accessdate=October 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302111532/http://datnewcudi.com/2010/01/20/kid-cudi-featured-on-snoop-doggs-more-malice/ |archivedate=March 2, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Cudi also teamed up with independent artist [[Johnny Polygon]], to [[remix]] Polygon's "The Riot Song", which appears on his mixtape ''Rebel Without Applause'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2010/02/14/johnny-polygon-feat-kid-cudi-riot-song-remix/#respond/ |title=Kid Cudi Featured on Johnny Polygon's "Riot Song" |publisher=Datnewcudi.com |date=February 14, 2010 |accessdate=October 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330202239/http://datnewcudi.com/2010/02/14/johnny-polygon-feat-kid-cudi-riot-song-remix/#respond/ |archivedate=March 30, 2012 |df= }}</ref> On April 20, 2010, Kid Cudi announced that the name of his second album would not be ''Cudder and the Revolution of Evolution'', but ''[[Man on the Moon II: The Legend of Mr. Rager]]''.<ref name="Man on the Moon 2">{{cite web|author=Kid Cudi|url=http://www.kidcudi.com/news/lend-me-your-eyesssss-1561.html|title=Lend Me Your Eyesssss|date=April 20, 2010|work=KidCudi.com|accessdate=April 24, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100423121659/http://www.kidcudi.com/news/lend-me-your-eyesssss-1561.html|archivedate=April 23, 2010|df=}}</ref><ref name="MTV UK">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/kid-cudi/news/209849-kid-cudi-makes-changes-to-his-albumagain|title=Kid Cudi Makes Changes To His Album... Again!|date=April 21, 2010|publisher=MTV UK|accessdate=April 24, 2010}}</ref> On June 11, 2010, Kid Cudi was arrested in the [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]] neighborhood of the [[Manhattan]] borough in New York City and charged with felony criminal mischief and possession of a controlled substance.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rodriguez|first=Jayson|title=Kid Cudi Arrested|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1641413/20100611/kid_cudi.jhtml|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 12, 2010|date=June 11, 2010}}</ref> Despite his arrest, he was released and made it to Manchester, Tennessee in time to play at [[Bonnaroo]].<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/957790/kid-cudi-plays-bonnaroo-despite-new-york-arrest Kid Cudi Plays Bonnaroo Despite New York Arrest]. Billboard.com (September 14, 2009). Retrieved on April 26, 2011.</ref>

The lead single from Cudi's second studio album, titled "[[Erase Me (song)|Erase Me]]", features Kanye West and was produced by [[Jim Jonsin]]. The song debuted on a Cleveland radio station June 30, 2010, and was officially released to Rhythm/Crossover radio on August 17, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rodriguez |first=Jayson |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1642855/20100701/kid_cudi.jhtml |title=Kid Cudi Debuts 'Erase Me,' With Kanye West, On Radio - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=July 1, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Koroma |first=Salima |url=http://beta.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11771/title.dx-news-bits-kid-cudi-lupe-fiasco |title=DX News Bits: Kid Cudi, Lupe Fiasco &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales &#124; HipHop DX |publisher=Beta.hiphopdx.com |date=July 22, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812093452/http://beta.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11771/title.dx-news-bits-kid-cudi-lupe-fiasco |archivedate=August 12, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |title=Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Arbitron Ratings, Music News and more! |publisher=FMQB |date= |accessdate=November 24, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411072813/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The title-track "[[Mr. Rager]]", was released as a promotional single shortly before the album's release. The album, released November 9, 2010, debuted at number three on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 169,000 copies.<ref name="DX-11-17">Jacobs, Allen (November 17, 2010). [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.13024/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-11-14-2010 "Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/14/2010"]. HipHopDX. Cheri Media Group.</ref> In its second week it crossed the 200,000 sales mark.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs |first=Allen |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.13114/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-11-21-2010 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/21/2010 &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>

In 2010, Kid Cudi appeared on several songs for Kanye West's weekly free music giveaway ''[[GOOD Fridays]]'', including "Good Friday", "Christian Dior Denim Flow" and "The Joy", the latter of which later became a [[bonus track]] on the [[Jay-Z]] and Kanye West collaborative album ''[[Watch the Throne]]'' (2011).

=== 2011–12: New direction and WZRD ===
{{Main article|WZRD (band)|WZRD (album)}}

In October 2010, Cudi had announced that he would be forming a rock band with frequent collaborator [[Dot da Genius]], tentatively called [[WZRD (band)|Wizard]].<ref>[http://www.ballerstatus.com/2010/10/29/kid-cudi-forms-rock-band-called-wizard/ Kid Cudi Forms Rock Band Called Wizard]. Ballerstatus (October 29, 2010). Retrieved on April 26, 2011.</ref> In early 2011, he announced that he would be releasing a mixtape titled ''A Man Named Scott'', reminiscent of his ''A Kid Named Cudi'' title, prior to the rock album.<ref name="rockalbum">[http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/01/kid-cudi-plans-rock-album-announces-a-man-named-scott-mixtape/ Kid Cudi plans rock album, announces A Man Named Scott mixtape « Consequence of Sound]. Consequenceofsound.net (January 28, 2011). Retrieved on April 26, 2011.</ref> On February 26, 2011, Cudi took to his Twitter account to announce that Dream On, the record label he launched back in 2009 with partners [[Plain Pat|Patrick "Plain Pat" Reynolds]] and producer [[Emile Haynie]], has been dissolved.<ref name=dreamon/> However, in an interview with ''Complex Magazine'' Cudi explained they were all still on good terms: "I wanted to try something new, and I wanted to take control of things myself. Those are still my guys, Pat and Emile, and I'm still going to work with them in the future. When we start working on ''Man on the Moon III'' I'll be calling them up to see if they want to be a part of it. I know Emile is definitely down. We had an issue, but we’re men and we were able to figure it out and move forward. There's no hard feelings."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/09/kid-cudi-puzzling-2011-cover-story/page/2 |title=Kid Cudi: Puzzling (2011 Cover Story) |publisher=Complex.com |date=September 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>

In March 2011, Cudi announced that a music video for "[[Marijuana (song)|Marijuana]]" would be released in the spring, followed by a music video for "[[Mr. Rager]]" in the summer, then he would release a [[short film]], directed by [[Shia LaBeouf]], inspired by his song "Maniac", with [[Cage (rapper)|Cage]], in October 2011.<ref>Roberts, Steven. (November 5, 2010) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651623/kid-cudi-shia-labeouf-picture-leaks-online.jhtml Kid Cudi/ Shia LaBeouf Picture Leaks Online – Music, Celebrity, Artist News]. MTV. Retrieved on April 26, 2011.</ref><ref name="twitter.com">{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=44090919305224192|date=March 5, 2011|title=maniac horror short will be released on halloween, rager short this summer, marijuana video this spring.  i got you guys, no worries}}</ref> In April 2011, while performing at New York City's Roseland Ballroom Kid Cudi announced he was launching his own record label. The new label, which he will be releasing his third studio album on is called Wicked Awesome Records. He also renamed his band on the same occasion to 2 Be Continuum, renaming it from the original Wizard. Kid Cudi explained his reasoning saying: "I needed something more original, something different, but it's still wizardry at its finest."<ref name="wicked awesome"/> In 2011, Cudi landed a songwriting placement on English singer [[Natalia Kills]]' debut album ''[[Perfectionist (album)|Perfectionist]]'', for the song "[[Free (Natalia Kills song)|Free]]".
[[File:Global Dance Fest 2011 @ Red Rocks.jpg|thumb|left|Kid Cudi performing at the Global Dance Festival in 2011.]]
On August 12, 2011, Kid Cudi released the music video for "[[No One Believes Me]]", directed by [[Fright Night (2011 film)|Fright Night]] director [[Craig Gillespie]]. The song, produced by Dot da Genius, features Cudi singing and contains elements of [[rock music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B005GYCXBY |title=No One Believes Me: Kid Cudi: Official Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref> On August 21, Cudi announced that he would no longer be releasing the ''A Man Named Scott'' mixtape, so that he can focus on his rock project and his third solo album ''Man on the Moon III''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cudlife.tumblr.com/post/9221598438/mixtape |title=Cud Life: Mixtape |publisher=Cudlife.tumblr.com |date=May 25, 2010 |accessdate=November 24, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726014139/http://cudlife.tumblr.com/post/9221598438/mixtape |archivedate=July 26, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref name="3rd MOTM">[http://cudlife.tumblr.com/post/7392420358/man-on-the-moon-iii-will-be-released-in-the-fall/ Kid Cudi announces a Fall 2012 release of his 3rd studio album « Cud Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217191906/http://cudlife.tumblr.com/post/7392420358/man-on-the-moon-iii-will-be-released-in-the-fall |date=December 17, 2013 }}. Retrieved on July 13, 2011.</ref> Kid Cudi released the music video for his second album's title-track "Mr. Rager", on September 8, 2011. The video has received all-positive reviews from critics and fans alike.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=psV5VtIEpOo |title=Kid Cudi - Mr Rager ( Music Video) RARE EDITION |publisher=YouTube |date=September 8, 2011 |accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>

Despite saying he will not do many more [[Guest appearance|features]] for other artists in ''Complex Magazine'''s October/November 2011 cover story,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/09/kid-cudi-puzzling-2011-cover-story/page/3 |title=Kid Cudi: Puzzling (2011 Cover Story) |publisher=Complex.com |date=September 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref> Cudi appeared on [[Bryan Greenberg]]'s second studio album ''We Don't Have Forever'' (2011), [[Travis Barker]]'s ''[[Give the Drummer Some]]'' (2011), [[The Knux]]'s ''[[Eraser (album)|Eraser]]'' (2011), and [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]]'s ''[[Ambition (Wale album)|Ambition]]'' (2011), respectively. On October 30, 2011, Cudi released ''[[Maniac (2011 film)|Maniac]]'', a [[Short film|short]] [[horror film]] co-starring [[Cage (rapper)|Cage]] and directed by [[Shia LaBeouf]], through his blog.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=131129794153824256|date=October 31, 2011|title=MANIAC Directed by Shia LaBeouf Starring Scott Mescudi and Chris Palko}}</ref> On November 13, 2011, a previously unreleased mixtape of material Cudi had recorded from 2002-2003, under the [[pseudonym]] Kid Mescudi, titled ''Rap Hard'' leaked online. On November 18, 2011 Cudi renamed his band for the second time to [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]] (pronounced W-Z-R-D).<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=137538406992449536|date=November 18, 2011|title=News update! Me and @DotDaGenius are no longer called 2 Be Continuum.  The world will call us W Z R D, which is short for WIZARD.}}</ref> He also announced that the upcoming rock project would be released on his 28th birthday, January 30, 2012.

In late 2011, Cudi was mentioned in a [[viral video]] by [[vlogger]] [[Ben Breedlove]], about his near death experiences.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/kid-cudi-responds-ben-breedlove-video-farewell-shortly-teen-fan-died-heart-condition-article-1.998401 | location=New York | work=Daily News | first=Ethan | last=Sacks | title=Kid Cudi touched by teen fan's video farewell | date=December 29, 2011}}</ref> After Breedlove's death on December 26, 2011, Cudi commented on his thoughts about inspiring the young kid. "I am so sad about Ben Breedlove," Kid Cudi wrote on his Tumblr blog. "I watched the video he left for the world to see, and him seeing me in detail, in his vision really warmed my heart. I broke down, I am to tears because I hate how life is so unfair. This has really touched my heart in a way I cant describe, this is why I do what I do. Why I write my life, and why I love you all so much. Life is really f---- up sometimes, but I know Ben is at Peace, and I hope he gets a chance to sit and talk with my Dad. We love you Ben. Forever. Thank you for loving me. To Ben’s family, you raised a real hero, he’s definitely mine. You have my love."

In January 2012, Cudi appeared on two songs from Chip tha Ripper's mixtape ''Tell Ya Friends'', "Ride 4 You" which also featured [[Far East Movement]] and "GloryUs", which credited the duo as they are collectively known, The Almighty GloryUs. This led to speculation that a long-awaited project from the two was underway. On January 31, Cudi announced through his Twitter feed that he had completed ''[[WZRD (album)|WZRD]]'' and that his next album was the collaborative effort with Chip tha Ripper.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=164511705265750017|date=February 1, 2012|title=3rd album finished.  Chip next, then my 4th}}</ref> In 2012, Cudi was featured on the [[The Hunger Games: Songs from District 12 and Beyond|soundtrack to the film]] ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'', crafting an original song for the film titled "The Ruler and the Killer". Referring to "The Ruler and the Killer", Cudi wrote on his Twitter feed: "I could not have done it without my producing partners on the project for the film, The legendary and Godly [[T-Bone Burnett|T Bone Burnett]] and [[Greg Wells]]!"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2012/03/01/kid-cudi-discusses-the-ruler-and-killer-from-the-hunger-games-soundtrack/ |title=Kid Cudi Discusses "The Ruler and Killer" from The Hunger Games Soundtrack |publisher=DatNewCudi |date=March 1, 2012 |accessdate=March 2, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305045222/http://datnewcudi.com/2012/03/01/kid-cudi-discusses-the-ruler-and-killer-from-the-hunger-games-soundtrack/ |archivedate=March 5, 2012 |df= }}</ref>

While working on the band's [[WZRD (album)|self-titled debut]], Cudi claims he had [[writer's block]] for almost 5 months because of his new [[sobriety]]; something that had never happened to him for such an extended period of time. According to Kid Cudi, bands that inspired the album include [[Electric Light Orchestra]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] and [[Pink Floyd]]. The album includes a song titled "[[Where Did You Sleep Last Night?]]", a [[Cover version|cover]] of the same titled song by [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], who in turn were inspired by blues guitar legend [[Lead Belly]]'s rendition of the [[Traditional music|traditional]] [[folk music|folk]] song.<ref name="listeningsession">{{cite web|author=|title=Kid Cudi & Dot Da Genius Host "WZRD" Listening Session in LA|url=http://datnewcudi.com/2012/02/14/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-host-wzrd-listening-session-in-la/|publisher=DatNewCudi|date=February 14, 2012|accessdate=February 20, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219062739/http://datnewcudi.com/2012/02/14/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-host-wzrd-listening-session-in-la/|archivedate=February 19, 2012|df=}}</ref> Following ''WZRD'''s release on February 28, 2012, the album debuted at #3 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 66,000 physical and [[Online distribution|digital copies]] in the United States.<ref name="HipHopDX">{{cite web|last=Jacobs|first=Allen|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18926/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-4-2012|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 3/4/2012|work=|publisher=HipHopDX|date=March 7, 2012|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> The album also debuted on the [[Rock Albums|Top Rock Albums]] and [[Alternative Albums|Top Alternative Albums]] at number one, and at #9 on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]] respectively.

=== 2012–13: ''Indicud'' ===
{{Main article|Indicud}}

In April 2012, in [[Geneseo, New York]], Cudi performed before a sold out crowd and premiered a hip hop song, his first since 2010. During his set, he performed a new record, tentatively titled "The Leader of the Delinquents", which he did [[a cappella]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://rapradar.com/2012/04/23/kid-cudi-performs-new-song-in-ny/ | title=Kid Cudi Performs New Song In NY | publisher=[[Rap Radar]] | work= | date=April 23, 2012| accessdate=March 10, 2013}}</ref> On April 25, 2012 Cudi was officially back to rapping with the release of "Dennis, Hook Me Up with Some More of That Whiskey!".<ref>{{cite news|author=Jacob Moore|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/04/premiere-kid-cudi-dennis-hook-me-up-with-some-more-of-that-whiskey|title=Premiere: Kid Cudi "Dennis, Hook Me Up With Some More Of That Whiskey!"|accessdate=March 17, 2013|newspaper=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=April 15, 2013}}</ref> The song, the first ever solely produced by Cudi himself, samples his 2010 song "Ghost!".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/ducidni/status/195362650736173057|title=Ghost!|last=Mescudi|first=Scott|date=April 25, 2012|work=[[Twitter]]|publisher=Kid Cudi|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> In June 2012, Cudi was seen in the music video for "[[Mercy (Kanye West song)|Mercy]]," the lead single from GOOD Music's [[compilation album]] ''[[Cruel Summer (GOOD Music album)|Cruel Summer]]'', in which he, along with other GOOD Music recording artists were featured on. Cudi was ultimately featured on two songs from the compilation, "The Morning" and a solo track originally meant for ''[[Man on the Moon II: The Legend of Mr. Rager|Man on the Moon II]]'' (2010), titled "Creepers", produced by [[Dan Black]].

In the summer of 2012, Cudi announced the title of his third studio album to be, ''[[Indicud]]'' when he [[Twitter|tweeted]]: "My new album is entitled ''indicud'', it will be my version of ''[[The Chronic 2001]]'', some songs i'll produce, others i'll feat &/or play songwriter".<ref name="indicud">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1686592/kid-cudi-new-album.jhtml|title=Kid Cudi Reveals New Album Title, Indicud|last=Dempsey|first=Brendan|date=June 5, 2012|work=MTV Newsroom|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=June 13, 2012}}</ref> On June 8, 2012, Cudi announced ''Indicud'', will be a [[Double album|double-disc album]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19982/title.kid-cudi-says-indicud-will-be-a-double-disc-album|title=Kid CuDi Says "indicud" Will Be A Double-Disc Album|last=Horowitz|first=Steven J.|date=June 11, 2012|work=|publisher=HipHopDX|accessdate=June 13, 2012}}</ref> On August 12, Kid Cudi released the lead single from ''Indicud'', a song titled "[[Just What I Am]]", featuring his friend and longtime collaborator [[King Chip]] (formerly Chip tha Ripper).<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/480471/kid-cudi-debuts-first-indicud-song-just-what-iam-listen |title=Kid Cudi Debuts First 'Indicud' Song, 'Just What Iam': Listen - The Juice |publisher=Billboard.com |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=August 13, 2012}}</ref> The album was announced to be released in early 2013 with Cudi focusing on scoring movies, followed by the third installment of the ''Man on the Moon'' series.<ref name="www.hiphopdx.com">{{cite web  | last =  | first =  | title = Kid Cudi Says He Lost His Mind But Found It, Details "indicud" & "Man On the Moon III" | url = http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.21685/title.kid-cudi-says-he-lost-his-mind-but-found-it-details-indicud-man-on-the-moon-iii | publisher =  | date =  | accessdate = October 29, 2012 }}</ref> Cudi then added that ''Indicud'' "will feature more uptempos and that it will consist of at most 17 new songs."<ref name="www.hiphopdx.com"/> The music video for "Just What I Am", which marked Cudi's directorial debut, premiered November 6, 2012 on [[VEVO]] and was shot in Los Angeles with fans invited to participate in the video’s shoot. On November 7, he revealed the album's second official single's title to be "[[Immortal (Kid Cudi song)|Immortal]]", and that it again was produced by himself like the two previous releases, "Just What I Am" and "[[King Wizard]]". He claimed the song "will make you feel amazing in the heart and soul."<ref name=immortal>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=266244210280263681|date=November 7, 2012|title=My official 2nd single is called "IMMORTAL", and it will make u feel amazing in the heart and soul.  We all have powers.  Comin soon}}</ref> The song was officially released via [[iTunes]] on March 14, 2013.<ref>{{cite web | title=Immortal – Single by Kid Cudi | url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/immortal-single/id620102269 | work=[[iTunes Store]] | publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] | accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref>

On March 14, 2013 Kid Cudi performed at [[MySpace]]’s [[South by Southwest|South by Southwest (SXSW)]] secret show in [[Austin, Texas]] and after performing his many hits, he previewed a new verse from ''Indicud''. He also revealed that the album would feature 18 tracks, while officially confirming ASAP Rocky and [[Michael Bolton]] as featured guests.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2013/03/15/kid-cudi-previews-new-music-at-sxsw-video/|title=KiD CuDi Previews New Music At SXSW (Video)|publisher=Complex Music|work=2DopeBoyz|date=March 15, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref> On March 16, Cudi announced that he would release the album's tracklist and [[cover art]] on April 2.<ref>
{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=313023528385531904|date=March 16, 2013|title=Revealing tracklisting and album cover April 2nd!!}}</ref> Three days later, Kid Cudi announced via Twitter that the album had officially been completed and turned in to his label, Universal Republic.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=314088357103800320|date=March 19, 2013|title=Album turnt in, spirit turnt up.  4th studio album wrapped. Mission impossible accomplished.  Hope u all love it as much as I do.}}</ref> On March 26, the album's cover art and tracklist was unveiled by [[Walmart]] and later [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/kid-cudi-unveils-indicud-album-art-and-tracklist|title=Kid Cudi Unveils "Indicud" Album Art and Tracklist|last=Weiss|first=Sam|date=March 26, 2013|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|publisher=Complex Media|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Later that day, Cudi appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' and performed the album's lead singles; "Just What I Am" and "Immortal", as well as premiering "Mad Solar", which he performed a cappella.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/watch-kid-cudi-debut-mad-solar-and-perform-immortal-on-jimmy-kimmel-live|title=Kid Cudi Unveils "Indicud" Album Art and Tracklist|last=Weiss|first=Sam|date=March 27, 2013|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|publisher=Complex Media|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name="JKvideo">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zke13NnYRJo Kid Cudi Performs "Just What I Am"] [[YouTube]], Retrieved March 28, 2013.</ref>

On April 2, 2013, Kid Cudi announced on [[Power 106]], that he was no longer under Kanye West's GOOD Music imprint. Cudi revealed he left the label on good terms, with him saying West respected his decision and will always be "big brother". Cudi's decision to move forward without West, was his desire to focus on his own imprint, Wicked Awesome Records and his friend, fellow rapper King Chip.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burgess |first=Omar |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23443/title.kid-cudi-announces-split-from-g-o-o-d-music |title=Kid Cudi Announces Split From G.O.O.D. Music &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=April 2, 2013 |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/kid-cudi-leaves-good-music/ |title=Kid Cudi: "I'm No Longer on G.O.O.D. Music" |publisher=Complex |date=April 2, 2013 |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Christina Lee |url=http://idolator.com/7450701/kid-cudi-label-wicked-awesome-leaving-good-music |title=Kid Cudi Talks Focusing On His Label, Now That He’s Left G.O.O.D. Music |publisher=Idolator.com |date=April 6, 2013 |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref> After ''Indicud'' [[Internet leak|leaked online]] in its entirety on April 9, 2013, Kid Cudi decided to push the album's release date up to April 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/04/10/kid-cudi-bumps-indicud-release-date-after-album-leak/ |title=Kid Cudi Bumps Indicud Release Date After Album Leak |publisher=Rapfix.mtv.com |date=April 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 20, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414010921/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/04/10/kid-cudi-bumps-indicud-release-date-after-album-leak |archivedate=April 14, 2013 |df= }}</ref>  The album went on to debut at #2 on the charts by moving 140,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/news/newsPage.cgi?news09365 |title=News |publisher=HITS Daily Double |date=April 23, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> In late 2013, Kid Cudi went on tour in support of ''Indicud'' on ''The Cud Life Tour 2013''. The tour was announced on July 15 with tickets going on sale the following day. Supporting acts on the tour included fellow American rappers [[Big Sean]], [[Tyler, The Creator]] and [[Logic (rapper)|Logic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missinfo.tv/index.php/kid-cudi-the-cud-life-tour/ |title=Kid Cudi Announces ‘The Cud Life Tour’ with Big Sean, Tyler, The Creator & Logic (Updated) |publisher=MissInfo.tv |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref>

=== 2013–14: ''Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon'' ===
{{Main article|Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon}}
While on tour, on October 16, 2013 Kid Cudi announced he would be releasing an [[extended play]] (EP), sometime in the next three months.<ref name="EP">{{cite web|author=Tardio, Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25841/title.kid-cudi-announces-man-on-the-moon-3-prelude-ep |title=Kid Cudi Announces "Man On The Moon 3" Prelude EP |work=[[HipHopDX]] |publisher=Cheri Media Group |date=October 16, 2013 |accessdate=January 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name="EP2">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/10/kid-cudi-ep-pre-man-on-the-moon |title=Kid Cudi Announces Prelude EP to "Man On The Moon 3" |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |publisher=[[Complex Media]] |date=October 16, 2013 |accessdate=January 31, 2014}}</ref> Cudi also revealed he would be producing it alongside Dot da Genius and that frequent collaborator King Chip, would appear on the EP.<ref name="EP"/> He then called the EP a [[Prelude (music)|prelude]] to his fourth album ''Man on the Moon III'', which he announced would be released in 2015.<ref name="EP"/> On October 19, 2013, Cudi revealed "Going to the Ceremony", a song he had released via online audio distribution platform [[SoundCloud]], earlier in July, would be included in the EP.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.republicrecords.com/new-music-kid-cudi-going-to-the-ceremony/ |title=Republic Records |publisher=Republic Records |date=July 6, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=391738472685248512|date=October 20, 2013|title=GOING TO THE CEREMONY will be included on the EP, as well as the never before released Day N Nite remix Dot &amp; I made the day after original!}}</ref> Cudi would also go on to reveal a [[remix]] of his hit single "Day 'n' Nite, which was briefly previewed on the intro of his 2008 breakout mixtape ''A Kid Named Cudi'', would also appear on the EP.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=391738656857149440|date=October 20, 2013|title=We basically made it the next day and kept it in the vault for the right time.  And the time is now ;)}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=391739115445555200|date=October 20, 2013|title=Wanna catch a snippet of it?? Play the intro to A Kid Named Cudi and listen reaaaal close.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=391739686906896384|date=October 20, 2013|title=A hidden clue thats just now being uncovered goin on 6 years later.}}</ref>
[[File:Kid Cudi Coachella 2014 1.jpg|thumb|Kid Cudi's performance at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] on April 19, 2014.]]
On November 25, 2013, via his Twitter, Cudi revealed the title of the EP to be ''[[Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/11/kid-cudi-makes-big-announcement/ |title=Kid Cudi Reveals Title Of Upcoming EP - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26390/title.kid-cudi-announces-satellite-flight-the-journey-to-mother-moon-ep |title=Kid Cudi Announces "Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon" EP &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |work=[[HipHopDX]] |publisher=Cheri Media Group |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> On December 16, 2013, Kid Cudi once again utilized SoundCloud to release "Satellite Flight", the EP's [[wikt:title track|title-track]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Davis |first=Justin |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/12/kid-cudi-satellite-flight |title=Listen to Kid Cudi's New Song "Satellite Flight" |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |publisher=Complex Media |date=December 16, 2013 |accessdate=January 14, 2014}}</ref> On January 27, 2014, Kid Cudi revealed on Twitter that ''Satellite Flight: Journey to Mother Moon'' would no longer be an EP, but a full-length album instead.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rose |first=Lila |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kid-cudi-announces-satellite-flight-is-now-an-album-not-ep-news.9090.html|title=Kid Cudi Announces "Satellite Flight" Is Now An Album, Not EP |work=HotNewHiphop |publisher=hot new hip hop |date=January 27, 2013 |accessdate=January 27, 2014}}</ref> In a February 2014 interview with [[MTV News]], Cudi discussed the EP's transition to a full-fledged album and called the project his best work yet: "I'm really excited because it's my best work, and it's a surprise. People weren't really expecting it. I've never done two albums within a year of each other."<ref>{{cite web|author=Cooper, Roman |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.27328/title.kid-cudi-calls-satellite-flight-album-his-best-work-/ |title=Kid Cudi Calls "Satellite Flight" Album His "Best Work" |work=[[HipHopDX]] |publisher=Cheri Media Group |date=February 2, 2014 |accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Robertson, Iyana |url=http://www.vibe.com/article/kid-cudi-calls-satellite-flight-his-best-work |title=Kid Cudi Calls "Satellite Flight" Album His "Best Work" |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |publisher=[[Spin Media]] |date=February 2, 2014 |accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>

On February 25, 2014, with only few hours' notice from Cudi, ''Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon'' was released exclusively to digital retailers. The album debuted at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 87,000 digital copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.27763/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-3-2-2014|last=Tardio |first=Andres  | title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 3/2/2014|publisher=''HipHopDX'' |date=March 5, 2014| accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref> On March 4, 2014 Cudi appeared on ''[[Chelsea Lately]]'', where he was interviewed by Oscar-nominated actress [[Gabourey Sidibe]], to promote ''Satellite Flight'' and the 2014 film ''[[Need for Speed (film)|Need for Speed]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fitzgerald, Trent |url=http://theboombox.com/kid-cudi-gabourey-sidibe-chelsea-lately/ |title=Kid Cudi Talks With Gabourey Sidibe on 'Chelsea Lately' |work=TheBoombox.com |publisher=THE BOOMBOX NETWORK |date=March 5, 2014 |accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref> On March 12, 2014, Cudi released a song titled "Hero", a collaboration with American singer-songwriter [[Skylar Grey]], recorded for the soundtrack to ''Need for Speed''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.directlyrics.com/new-music-kid-cudi-hero-news.html |title=New Music: Kid Cudi feat. Skylar Grey - 'Hero' |publisher=Directlyrics.com |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lobenfeld |first=Claire |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/03/kid-cudi-feat-skylar-grey-need-for-speed-ost |title=Hear New Kid Cudi Song "Hero" Featuring Skylar Grey |publisher=Complex |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> On March 15, 2014, Cudi appeared on ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'', where he promoted the album, discussed the state of hip-hop, [[Suicidal ideation|suicidal thoughts]], ''Need for Speed'', and performed the song "Internal Bleeding", from the album.<ref name="arsenio">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/kid-cudi-talks-suicidal-thoughts-state-hip-hop-arsenio-hall-0 |title=Kid Cudi Talks Suicidal Thoughts & The State Of Hip-Hop On 'Arsenio' |publisher=Vibe |date=March 15, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/15/kid-cudi-arsenio-hall_n_4971684.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Ryan | last=Kristobak | title=Kid Cudi: 'There Would Be No Drake'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kohn |first=Daniel |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/03/kid-cudi-drake-arsenio-hall |title=Kid Cudi Says "There Would Be No Drake" if Cudi Rapped About His Cars |publisher=Complex |date=March 15, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

In April 2014, Cudi appeared on the cover of the inaugural issue of ''Fat Man'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopwired.com/2014/04/23/kid-cudi-covers-inaugural-issue-fat-man-magazine-photo/ |title=KiD CuDi Covers Inaugural Issue Of FAT MAN Magazine [PHOTO |publisher=Hip-Hop Wired |date=April 23, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=David Fischer |url=http://www.highsnobiety.com/2014/04/22/kid-cudi-covers-issue-a-of-fat-man-magazine/ |title=Kid Cudi Covers Issue A of Fat Man Magazine • Highsnobiety |publisher=Highsnobiety.com |date= |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> On April 24, 2014, while being honored as a mental health advocate by Didi Hirsch Mental Health Services, at the Beverly Hilton in Los Angeles, Cudi offered a special performance during their annual Erasing the Stigma Leadership Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20140408006438/en/Kid-Cudi-Ronda-Rousey-Natasha-Tracy-Center#.U14AsvldWSo |title=Kid Cudi, Ronda Rousey and Natasha Tracy Take Center Stage at Didi Hirsch’s 18th Annual Erasing the Stigma Leadership Awards |publisher=Business Wire |date=April 8, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> On May 2, 2014, it was announced Cudi would headline Chicago's [[North Coast Music Festival]], along with [[West Coast hip hop|West Coast rapper]] [[Snoop Dogg]].<ref>{{cite web|author=G. Valentino Ball |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/05/snoop-dogg-kid-cudi-chicago-north-coast-festival/ |title=Snoop Dogg, Kid Cudi To Headline Chicago's North Coast Music Festival |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=May 2, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-05-01/entertainment/chi-north-coast-festival-lineup-20140501_1_north-coast-music-festival-bassnectar-snoop-dogg |title=North Coast festival lineup; Snoop Dogg, Bassnectar headline North Coast fest - Chicago Tribune |publisher=Articles.chicagotribune.com |date=May 1, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> On May 11, 2014 Cudi revealed he would be writing and directing a short film for the ''Satellite Flight'' album cut "Balmain Jeans": "Developing a short film for "Balmain Jeans", a story about a spontaneous electric connection between two strangers."<ref>{{cite web|last=Kujundzic |first=Petar |url=http://hypetrak.com/2014/05/kid-cudi-to-write-direct-short-film-for-balmain-jeans/ |title=KiD CuDi to Write & Direct Short Film For ‘Balmain Jeans’ |publisher=Hypetrak |date=May 11, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=C. Vernon Coleman |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/05/kid-cudi-writing-directing-short-film-balmain-jeans/ |title=Kid Cudi Writing & Directing Short Film For "Balmain Jeans" - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=May 11, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

=== 2015–16: ''Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven'' ===
{{Main article|Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven}}

In a January 2015 interview, at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], Kid Cudi expressed the possibility of releasing another album before the release of ''Man on the Moon III'': "I'm always making music. The beauty in that is that I have a lot of material. And I'm actually thinking that it would be good to release something in the meantime, before ''Man on the Moon III'' comes out. Another Kid Cudi album, it's just kind of along the lines of what I did with ''Indicud'' or ''Satellite Flight'', which is just its own standalone thing but still a Kid Cudi album. The ''Man on the Moon III'' album is something that's gonna take some time but I know the fans are gonna be patient and I really appreciate that guys, thank you for your patience. But ''Man on the Moon III'' is coming, there may be an album before that just to tide you over."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themaskedgorilla.com/kid-cudi-planning-to-release-album-before-man-on-the-moon-3/ |title=Kid Cudi Planning To Release Album Before Man On The Moon: III |publisher=The Masked Gorilla |date=January 30, 2015 |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsonhits.com/kid-cudi-planning-to-release-new-album-before-man-on-the-moon-iii/ |title=Kid Cudi Planning To Release New Album Before Man On The Moon: III &#124; Hits On Hits. Stay Ahead Of The Game |publisher=Hitsonhits.com |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref>

On March 3, 2015, Cudi officially released his first song since his album ''Satellite Flight'', was put on the market. The song, which is titled "Love," was originally recorded for ''Satellite Flight'',  and samples Ratatat's "Sunblocks" and has been received with positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2095432/kid-cudi-cheer-up-love/|title=Kid Cudi Wants You To Cheer Up And Listen To 'Love'|author=|date=|work=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2015/03/03/kid-cudi-love-new-song-listen-amazing/|title=[LISTEN] Kid Cudi’s ‘Love’ — Listen To Hot New Song - Hollywood Life|author=Shira Benozilio|date=|work=Hollywood Life}}</ref> On April 4, 2015, Cudi announced via Twitter that he would be releasing a new album titled ''[[Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven]]''. On October 27, 2015, Cudi announced the new album will be released on December 4, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2015/04/05/kid-cudi-announces-new-album-speedin-bullet-to-heaven/|title=Kid Cudi Announces New Album ‘Speedin’ Bullet to Heaven’|author=|date=|work=Rap-Up}}</ref> He also leaked two songs off the project, "Wedding Tux" and "Judgemental Cunt".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2015/10/27/kid-cudi-announces-release-date-speedin-bullet-to-heaven-december/ |title=Kid Cudi Announces Release Date For "Speedin’ Bullet To Heaven" |publisher=BallerStatus.com |date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> In November 2015 Cudi announced a ''Especial Tour'', that will bring the rapper to various theaters all across the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/54435/20151113/kid-cudi-especial-tour-speedin-bullet-to-heaven.htm|title=Kid Cudi Announces 'Especial' Tour Supporting 'Speedin Bullet To Heaven'|author=|date=|work=Music Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2015/11/12/kid-cudi-announces-especial-tour/|title=Kid Cudi Announces ‘Especial’ Tour|author=|date=|work=Rap-Up}}</ref> On December 1, 2015, Cudi announced the cancellation of his ''Especial Tour'', due to various reasons, such as production and personal issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kid-cudi-cancels-especial-tour-news.18927.html|title=Kid Cudi Cancels "Especial" Tour|author=Kevin Goddard|date=December 2, 2015|work=HotNewHipHop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/detroit/index.ssf/2015/12/rapper_kid_cudi_cancels_tour_t.html|title=Why Kid Cudi says he cancelled his entire concert tour|author=|date=|work=MLive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hypebeast.com/2015/12/kid-cudi-cancels-especial-tour|title=Kid Cudi Cancels 'Especial' Tour|author=|date=|work=Hypebeast}}</ref> To make up for postponing the concert tour, Cudi released the album's [[wikt:title-track|title-track]] as the second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2618448/kid-cudi-speedin-bullet-2-heaven-song-cancels-tour/|title=Kid Cudi's New Single Will Remind You To Smile About Your Falls|author=|date=|work=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/6784804/kid-cudi-cancels-especial-tour-speedin-bullet-2-heaven|title=Kid Cudi Cancels 'Especial' Tour, Releases 'Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven'|author=|date=|work=Billboard}}</ref>

===2016–present: ''Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin''' and Kids See Ghosts===
{{Main article|Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin'|Kids See Ghosts|Kids See Ghosts (album)}}
In March 2016, Kid Cudi performed at McDowell Mountain Music Festival in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicfestivalwizard.com/festivals/mcdowell-mountain-music-festival-2016/ |title=McDowell Mountain Festival 2016 &#124; The MFW Music Festival Guide |website=Musicfestivalwizard.com |date=March 13, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> In an early April 2016 interview with ''Billboard'', when asked about ''Man on the Moon III'', Cudi responded with: "I came up with ''Man on the Moon'' when I was a young man. People change their vibe! We can follow the same template and do the five-act split. Sonically, I’m still going to be where I’m at. Honestly, I was ready to live up to the obligation and do '''Man on the Moon III''. I haven’t been dicking around. I was planning on doing it after ''Speedin' Bullet''. But the ''Speedin’ Bullet'' response tore me up. It made me realize what’s most important. I’m getting back on the bike again and doing what I do best: me."<ref>{{cite web|author=Brad Wete |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7341594/kid-cudi-reveals-struggle-with-drugs-and-depression-working-with-kanye-west-new-music |title=Kid Cudi Reveals His Struggle With Drugs and Depression |publisher=Billboard |date=April 22, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> On April 22, 2016, Kid Cudi announced he would be releasing a new studio album, slated for a summer unveiling.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=723625184016519169|date=April 22, 2016|title=New album this summer}}</ref>

On May 11, 2016, amidst rumors that he was set to release ''Man on the Moon III'', Cudi revealed the title of his sixth solo album would be ''[[Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin']]'', through online mobile video-sharing and social networking service [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Low |first=Carver |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kid-cudi-reveals-title-for-his-upcoming-album-news.21568.html |title=Kid Cudi Reveals Title For His Upcoming Album |website=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=May 11, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> On June 1, 2016, Cudi announced that he has two upcoming albums. One set to be released in the summer, while the other would be released in the fall. He added that one of them is completed.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=738062240000049153|date=June 1, 2016|title=So my plan is to release 2 albums this year. One for the summer and another for the fall. I finished this new one already.  Fine tuning now}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hiphopearly.com/kid-cudi-releasing-one-album-this-summer-another-in-the-fall/|title=Kid Cudi releasing one album this summer and another in the fall|publisher=HipHopEarly|accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref> On September 26, 2016, Kid Cudi unveiled the track-list for ''Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin''' via Twitter, which revealed guest spots from [[Travis Scott]], [[André 3000]], [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Willow Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Darville |first=Jordan |url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/09/26/kid-cudi-passion-pain-and-demon-slayin-tracklist |title=Here Is The Tracklist For Kid Cudiâ€™s Passion, Pain & Demon Slayinâ€™ |publisher=The Fader |date=September 26, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=780556578579701760|date=September 26, 2016|title="Passion, Pain &amp; Demon Slayin"  Sept. 30th}}</ref>

Although there was a discrepancy between him and [[Kanye West]], West later made an offer of peace and a song featuring him and Cudi subsequently surfaced online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2939187/kanye-west-kid-cudi-newly-surfaced-collab/ |title=Kid Cudi and Kanye West make song against haters |last=Roth |first=Madeline |date=October 3, 2016 |access-date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> ''Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin’'' was announced to be issued first via digital distribution on December 16, 2016, with the physical release on December 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/passion-pain-demon-slayin/id1181775706 |title=Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin' by Kid Cudi on Apple Music |website=Itunes.apple.com |date=January 30, 1984 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KidCudi|author=The Chosen One|number=804357268242169856|date=December 1, 2016|title=PASSION, PAIN &amp; DEMON SLAYIN' DEC 16 digital DEC 23 physical}}</ref> Cudi has also shared the song "Baptized in Fire," which features Travis Scott (with whom Cudi collaborated extensively with on 2016's ''[[Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight]]'').<ref>{{cite web|last=Schwartz |first=Danny |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/kid-cudi-baptized-in-fire-feat-travis-scott-new-song.1972096.html |title=Kid Cudi - Baptized In Fire Feat. Travis Scott &#124; Stream [New Song&#93; |website=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> On March 1, 2017, Kid Cudi performed the song "Kitchen", with a [[string orchestra]], live on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/02/kid-cudi-and-a-string-orchestra-perform-kitchen-on-fallon-watch/|title=Kid Cudi and a string orchestra perform “Kitchen” on Fallon — watch|date=February 9, 2017|work=consequenceofsound.net|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref>

On August 15, 2017, Cudi announced a national concert tour by the name of Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin' Tour; with the first date on September 30 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7905033/kid-cudi-passion-pain-demon-slaying-tour-dates|title=Kid Cudi Announces Dates for Passion, Pain & Demon Slaying Tour|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2017/08/kid-cudi-passion-pain-demon-slayin-tour|title=Kid Cudi Announces Passion, Pain, & Demon Slayin' Tour|website=Complex}}</ref>

In 2018 Cudi and [[Kanye West]] formed a duo known as [[Kids See Ghosts]], and produced an album with the same name, ''[[Kids See Ghosts (album)|Kids See Ghosts]]'', which was released on June 8, 2018.<ref name="spin-kayne">{{cite web|title=Kanye West Announces New Album With Kid Cudi|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/04/kanye-west-kid-cudi-album-kids-see-ghosts-release-date/|website=Spin|accessdate=April 19, 2018|date=April 19, 2018}}</ref>

On October 23, 2018, in response to a fan on Twitter, Cudi revealed he had begun working on his seventh solo album. Although he said he would be taking his time to create his forthcoming LP, Cudi projected a 2019 release.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8481417/kid-cudi-new-album-details</ref><ref>http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/10/kid-cudi-new-album-announcement/</ref>

==Acting career==
[[File:Kid Cudi pointing.jpg|Kid Cudi appearing at [[Santa Clara University]] in 2009.|thumb]]
In 2010, Kid Cudi made a guest appearance on American television drama ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]'', starring as himself and performing his ''Man on the Moon II'' single "[[Erase Me (song)|Erase Me]]", during the episode.<ref>{{cite web|author=Becky Bain |url=http://www.idolator.com/5704761/kid-cudi-one-tree-hill |title=Kid Cudi Plays Himself On ‘One Tree Hill’, Becomes The Most Convincing Actor On The Show &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date=December 1, 2010 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Kid Cudi also began starring in the [[HBO]] comedy series ''[[How to Make It in America]]'', as part of the main cast, being credited by his birth name Scott Mescudi, until its cancellation after two seasons.<ref>{{cite web |author = HBO |author-link = HBO |title = Kid Cudi in ''How to Make it in America'' |url = http://www.hbo.com/how-to-make-it-in-america/cast-and-crew/domingo-brown/bio/scott-kid-cudi-mescudi.html |accessdate = March 7, 2010}}</ref> On October 31, 2010, Kid Cudi released a [[short film]], directed by [[Shia LeBeouf]], in which he and fellow American rapper [[Cage (rapper)|Cage]], star as [[French language|French]]-speaking [[serial killer]]s. The short film, titled ''[[Maniac (2011 film)|Maniac]]'', was inspired by Cudi's song of the same name, from his 2010 album ''Man on the Moon II'' and is an homage to the 1992 [[Belgian]] [[black comedy]] crime mockumentary, ''[[Man Bites Dog (film)|Man Bites Dog]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/01/maniac-shia-labeouf-kid-cudi_n_1070546.html |title='Maniac' By Shia LaBeouf, Starring Kid Cudi (VIDEO) (NSFW) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=January 9, 2014 |first=Mallika |last=Rao}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/10/video-kid-cudi-maniac-directed-by-shia-labeouf |title=Video: Kid Cudi "Maniac" (Directed by Shia LaBeouf) + Bonus Interview |publisher=Complex |date=October 31, 2011 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> In May 2012, [[Kanye West]] premiered a short film he directed, titled ''[[Cruel Summer (film)|Cruel Summer]],'' at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]. According to [[MTV]], Kid Cudi is the lead character, playing a "car thief who falls for a blind Arabian princess." The film was shown on seven different screens that turned on and off, giving various angles of each shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/46635-kanye-wests-cruel-summer-film-premieres-at-cannes-starring-kid-cudi/ |title=Kanye West's Cruel Summer Film Premieres at Cannes, Starring Kid Cudi &#124; News |publisher=Pitchfork |date=May 24, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref>

In October 2012, it was announced Cudi would star in an [[Independent film|indie]] [[romantic comedy]] titled ''[[Two Night Stand]]'', alongside [[Analeigh Tipton]] and [[Miles Teller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474646/kid-cudi-joins-two-night-stand-romantic-comedy |title=Kid Cudi Joins 'Two Night Stand' Romantic Comedy |publisher=Billboard |date=October 15, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1695641/kid-cudi-two-night-stand-movie.jhtml |title=Kid Cudi To Star In Rom-Com 'Two Night Stand' - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV.com |date=October 16, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> Also in 2012, it was revealed Cudi would star in an indie [[thriller film]] titled ''Tacoma'', alongside [[Patricia Clarkson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/kid-cudi-breaking-in-feature-film-acting-w-roles-in-2-indies-apocalyptic-comedy-thriller |title=Kid Cudi Breaking In Feature Film Acting w/ Roles In 2 Indies (Apocalyptic Comedy & Thriller) &#124; Shadow and Act |publisher=Blogs.indiewire.com |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://datnewcudi.com/2012/07/29/kid-cudi-cast-as-yanni-in-tacoma-thriller-film-due-out-in-2013/ |title=Kid Cudi Cast as Yanni in "Tacoma" Thriller Film Due Out in 2013 &#124; Dat New 'Cudi' |publisher=Datnewcudi.com |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219122934/http://datnewcudi.com/2012/07/29/kid-cudi-cast-as-yanni-in-tacoma-thriller-film-due-out-in-2013/ |archivedate=December 19, 2013 |df= }}</ref> In 2013, Cudi guest starred in the animated TV series ''[[The Cleveland Show]]'', [[voice actor|voicing]] a character named Devon, in the Season 4 episode "Brownsized".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2013/03/04/kid-cudi-guests-on-the-cleveland-show-full-episode/ |title=Kid Cudi Guests on ‘The Cleveland Show’ |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, he also guest starred on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] comedy series ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'', where he played a criminal named Dustin Whitman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/2013/11/kid-cudi-will-appear-brooklyn-nine-nine-tonight/ |title=Kid Cudi Will Appear On 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Tonight - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, it was revealed Cudi would then star in ''[[Goodbye World]]'', alongside [[Adrian Grenier]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Montanez |first=Eric |url=http://hypetrak.com/2013/06/kid-cudi-in-goodbye-world-trailer/ |title=KiD CuDi Stars in ‘Goodbye World’ Trailer |publisher=Hypetrak |date=June 13, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/adrian-greniers-goodbye-world-acquired-samuel-goldwyn-phase-4-films/ |title=Adrian Grenier's 'Goodbye World' Acquired by Samuel Goldwyn, Phase 4 Films |publisher=TheWrap |date=October 21, 2013 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

In January 2013, Cudi was cast in the film adaptation of ''[[Need for Speed (film)|Need for Speed]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://deadline.com/dreamworks-revs-need-for-speed-rap-producer-scott-kid-cudi-mescudi-cast/ |title= DreamWorks Revs ‘Need For Speed’; Rap Producer Scott ‘Kid Cudi’ Mescudi Cast | first= Mike, Jr. | last= Fleming | publisher= Deadline.com | date=January 14, 2013| accessdate= February 19, 2013}}</ref> ''Need for Speed'', which is Cudi's [[feature film]] debut, was released by Touchstone Pictures on March 14, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vilanova |first=John |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/03/07/need-for-speed-kid-cudi-interview/ |title='Need for Speed': Kid Cudi reveals 'Breaking Bad' bromance &#124; Inside Movies &#124; EW.com |publisher=Insidemovies.ew.com |date=March 7, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> In June 2013, it was revealed Cudi would appear in [[Mark Webber (actor)|Mark Webber]]'s film ''[[The Ever After]]'', alongside [[Teresa Palmer]] and [[Melissa Leo]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Dave McNary |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/teresa-palmer-melissa-leo-ever-after-1200493601/ |title=Teresa Palmer, Melissa Leo Starring In ‘The Ever After’ |publisher=Variety |date=June 6, 2013 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> On November 10, 2014, Cudi guest starred on the [[CBS]] American television series ''[[Scorpion (TV series)|Scorpion]]'', as Peyton Temple, a musical prodigy who created a controversial [[algorithm]] that generates the perfect hit pop song, who later helps Scorpion investigate the murder of his friend who was a music industry blogger.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1991236/exclusive-kid-cudi-scorpion-clip/ |title=Watch This Exclusive Kid Cudi 'Scorpion' Clip For His Acting And The Well-Timed Macklemore Joke |publisher=MTV |date=November 7, 2014 |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Abrams |first=Natalie |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/09/29/scorpion-kid-cudi-method-man-cbs |title='Scorpion' enlists Kid Cudi, Method Man as rivals |publisher=EW.com |date=September 29, 2014 |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref> In February 2014, it was announced Cudi would appear in ''[[Entourage (film)|Entourage]]'' (2015), the film adaptation of the popular HBO [[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|TV series of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/entourages-ari-gold-finds-his-new-lloyd-its-kid-cudi/ |title='Entourage's Ari Gold Finds His New Lloyd: It's Kid Cudi |publisher=Deadline.com |date=February 20, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Yohance Kyles |url=http://allhiphop.com/2014/02/24/kid-cudi-joins-the-cast-of-entourage-movie/ |title=Kid Cudi Joins The Cast Of "Entourage" Movie |publisher=AllHipHop.com |date=February 24, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Serafino |first=Jason |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/02/kid-cudi-cast-in-entourage-movie |title=Kid Cudi Is Set To Play Ari Gold's New Assistant In The "Entourage" Movie |publisher=Complex |date=February 21, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>

On April 11, 2014, it was announced Cudi would star in a film titled ''[[James White (film)|James White]]'', alongside [[Christopher Abbott]] and [[Cynthia Nixon]]. In addition to starring in the film, it was revealed Cudi would also be curating the [[Film score|film's score]] as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Serafino |first=Jason |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/04/james-white-kickstarter |title=Check Out the Kickstarter for "James White," Starring Kid Cudi and Christopher Abbott |publisher=Complex |date=April 11, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> In January 2015, Cudi revealed he played a [[homosexual]] character in ''James White'': "This was way different than anything else I've ever done. It was dope to do that. I felt like I had a responsibility to present a different walk in life from that world." Although his character's sexuality is not outwardly discussed during the film, the original script included a coming-out scene and a kiss between Cudi and a male friend, played by David Call: "I didn't flinch. I'm secure with mine," Cudi told an audience after the film's premiere. "I'm an artist—it's all about playing characters that are intriguing and stimulating."<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2058980/kid-cudi-gay-kissing-scenes-cut-james-white/ |title=Kid Cudi Is Bummed His Gay Kissing Scenes Were Cut From 'James White' |publisher=MTV |date=January 25, 2015 |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sundance-2015/6450862/kid-cudi-dishes-on-his-deleted-male-on-male-kissing-scenes-in-james-white-sundance |title=Kid Cudi Dishes on His Deleted Male-on-Male Kissing Scenes in New Film James White at Sundance |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref>

Also in January 2015, Cudi revealed he had just finished filming a movie titled ''[[Vincent-N-Roxxy]]'', alongside [[Zoe Kravitz]] and [[Emile Hirsch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6443646/kid-cudi-wraps-movie-with-zoe-kravitz-Vincent-N-Roxxy |title=Kid Cudi Wraps Movie With Zoe Kravitz |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://allhiphop.com/2015/01/19/kid-cudi-zoe-kravitz-emile-hirsch-movie-vincent-n-roxxy/ |title=Kid Cudi Set To Star In Movie With Zoe Kravitz & Emile Hirsch |publisher=AllHipHop |date=January 19, 2015 |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref> When speaking on ''Vincent-N-Roxxy'', Cudi said: "this movie that I have coming out soon that’s my first [[villain]] role. It’s very violent and very disturbing […] I play kind of like a [[drug lord]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/2015/11/kid-cudi-plays-gay-scores-james-white/|title=After Playing A Gay Man In 'James White', Kid Cudi Readies For A More "Disturbing" Role|author=|date=|work=Vibe}}</ref> On February 19, 2015, it was announced that Cudi would be taking over the mic duties for [[Reggie Watts]], on [[IFC (U.S. TV network)|IFC]]'s television series, [[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|''Comedy Bang! Bang!'']]. Cudi's first episode as [[Scott Aukerman]]'s co-host, aired July 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifc.com/shows/comedy-bang-bang/blog/2015/02/comedy-bang-bang-passes-the-mic-to-kid-cudi |title=Comedy Bang! Bang! - Comedy Bang! Bang! Passes the Mic to Kid Cudi – IFC |publisher=Ifc.com |date= |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/tv/2015/12/scott-aukerman-comedy-bang-bang-interview/3/|title=Scott Aukerman Talks ‘Comedy Bang! Bang!’: Interview|author=|date=|work=UPROXX}}</ref> As the in-house [[disc jockey]], Cudi crafted original music for the show and appeared in several [[Sketch comedy|skits]] throughout season four.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/12/02/comedy-bang-bang-reggie-watts-kid-cudi-clip|title=Reggie Watts: Kid Cudi taught art of band-leading in Comedy Bang! Bang! - EW.com|author=|date=|work=Entertainment Weekly's EW.com}}</ref> The December 10 Christmas edition of ''Comedy Bang! Bang!'', marked the season finale and Cudi's final episode as bandleader.<ref>{{cite web |author=Josiah Hughes |title=Kid Cudi Exits 'Comedy Bang Bang' |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/kid_cudi_exits_comedy_bang_bang |date=December 11, 2015 |accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://splitsider.com/2015/12/last-nights-comedy-bang-bang-finale-was-kid-cudis-last-episode/|title=Last Night’s ‘Comedy Bang! Bang!’ Finale Was Kid Cudi’s Last Episode|author=|date=|work=Splitsider}}</ref>

In July 2016, it was announced Cudi would join the cast of FOX's ''[[Empire (2015 TV series)|Empire]]'', debuting in the third season of the series as "an independent musician who is a rival to [[Hakeem Lyon|Hakeem]] ([[Bryshere Y. Gray|Bryshere "Yazz" Gray]]) both in the studio and in life."<ref>{{cite web|last=Stack |first=Tim |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/20/empire-kid-cudi-season-3 |title=Empire: Kid Cudi to play Hakeem's rival in season 3 |website=EW.com |date=July 18, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66957-kid-cudi-joins-the-cast-of-empire/ |title=Kid Cudi Joins the Cast of "Empire" |publisher=Pitchfork |date=July 20, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Cudi would later exit the role due to creative differences.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harling |first=Danielle |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.40256/title.kid-cudi-to-be-replaced-by-romeo-miller-on-empire |title=Kid Cudi Leaves "Empire" Over Creative Differences |publisher=HipHopDX |date=September 2, 2016 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>

==Artistry==
===Musical style===
[[File:Kid Cudi Wanderland.jpg|thumb|220px|left|Kid Cudi's atmospheric music has a progressive mixture of hip-hop, [[indie rock]], [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] and [[Psychedelic music|psychedelia]] elements.]]
Kid Cudi's musical style has been described as "an atmospheric take on melodic rap, with a dollop of charming, off-key singing".<ref name="spin"/> He has also been called "introspective, with the ability to lay his insecurities on record and expose his fallibility."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/is-rap-finally-breaking-its-mental-health-taboo-the-lancet-kendrick-lamar|title=Is Rap Finally Breaking Its Mental Health Taboo?|author=|date=|work=NOISEY}}</ref> In 2015, Kris Ex of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', wrote "he's always been an emotional artist, dealing with expansive and nebulous feelings in acute and often destructive ways."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6792578/kid-cudi-speedin-bullet-2-heaven-album-review|title=Kid Cudi Grapples With Life's Lows on 'Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven': Album Review|author=|date=|work=Billboard}}</ref> Kid Cudi's sound is what inspired and led [[Kanye West]] to create his cathartic ''[[808s & Heartbreak]]'' (2008),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/overtones/9725-the-coldest-story-ever-told-the-influence-of-kanye-wests-808s-heartbreak/|title=The Coldest Story Ever Told: The Influence of Kanye West’s 808s & Heartbreak - Pitchfork|author=|date=|work=pitchfork.com}}</ref> with West later stating that he and Cudi were "the originators of the style, kinda like what [[Alexander McQueen]] is to [[fashion]]…. Everything else is just [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]] and [[H&M]]."<ref name="2009interview"/><ref name="revisiting">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.2724/title.revisiting-kid-cudis-man-on-the-moon-the-end-of-day-5-years-later|title=- HipHopDX|author=|date=January 30, 2015|work=HipHopDX}}</ref> West also complimented Cudi by saying, "His writing is just so pure and natural and important."<ref>Hoard, Christian. "Kid Cudi: Hip-Hop's Sensitive Soul." ''Rolling Stone''. ''Music Index''.</ref> In March 2014, Cudi talked about wanting to provide guidance for young listeners with his music: "my mission statement since day one […] all I wanted to do was help kids not feel alone, and stop committing suicide."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/2014/03/kid-cudi-talks-suicidal-thoughts-state-hip-hop-arsenio-hall-0/|title=Kid Cudi Talks Suicidal Thoughts & The State Of Hip-Hop On ‘Arsenio’|author=|date=|work=Vibe}}</ref>

In a 2013 article for ''The BoomBox'', the author wrote: "On [''A Kid Named Cudi''], Cudi raps and croons over samples and interpolations of [[Gnarls Barkley]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Band of Horses]], [[J Dilla]], [[Nosaj Thing]], [[N.E.R.D.]] and [[Outkast]]. He melded [[indie rock]], electronica and [[dubstep]] seamlessly with hip-hop without pandering or reaching. Before [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] broke through with 2009’s ''[[So Far Gone (mixtape)|So Far Gone]]'', rapping and singing over Swedish indie poppers [[Lykke Li]] and [[Peter Bjorn and John]], Cudi tweaked with multi-genre covers and seamless transitions between singing and rapping."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theboombox.com/revisiting-kid-cudi-a-kid-named-cudi-mixtape-2008|title=Revisiting A Kid Named Cudi|author=|date=August 29, 2013|work=The Boombox}}</ref> In a 2009 interview with [[HipHopDX]], when speaking on his debut album Cudi stated: "Well one thing I wanted to do was combine sounds that really bring out intense moods."<ref name="revisiting"/>

Kid Cudi's music has also been described as [[trip hop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chscommunicator.com/a-and-e/2014/03/24/album-review-kid-cudi-satellite-flight/|title=The Communicator :   ALBUM REVIEW: Kid Cudi, "Satellite Flight: The Journey to Mother Moon"|author=|date=|work=The Communicator}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/musicandnightlife/kid-cudi-shoots-for-the-moon-but-is-slow-to-lift-off-b9999110z1-224356971.html|title=Concert Review - Kid Cudi shoots for the moon, but is slow to lift off|author=Piet Levy|date=|work=jsonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.1562/title.kid-cudi-man-on-the-moon-ii-the-legend-of-mr-rager|title=- HipHopDX|author=|date=November 8, 2010|work=HipHopDX}}</ref> Furthermore, he is known for [[Harmonization|harmonizing]] and [[humming]] in his music, which helps formulate his signature sound.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://djbooth.net/news/entry/2016-11-23-why-im-thankful-kid-cudi-humming|title=Why I’m Thankful For… Kid Cudi’s Humming - DJBooth Article|work=djbooth.net|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/realtalk/travis-scott-kid-cudi-through-the-late-night-song-lyrics/|title=Travi$ Scott Brings Out Kid Cudi's Good Side On 'Through The Late Night'|date=September 7, 2016|work=uproxx.com|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vashtie.com/blog/listen-kid-cudis-passion-pain-demon-slayin-hums/|title=Listen To Kid Cudi's 'Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin'' With Hums Only - VASHTIE|date=December 22, 2016|work=vashtie.com|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref> On 2011's ''[[WZRD (album)|WZRD]]'' and 2015's ''[[Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven]]'', Cudi incorporated the use of [[screaming (music)|screamed vocals]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21351-speedin-bullet-2-heaven/|title=Kid Cudi: Speedin' Bullet 2 Heaven Album Review - Pitchfork|work=pitchfork.com|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/album-review-kid-cudi-speedin-bullet-2-heaven/|title=Album Review: Kid Cudi – Speedin’ Bullet 2 Heaven|date=December 10, 2015|work=consequenceofsound.net|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref> and can be heard [[yodeling]] on his 2016 album ''[[Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin']]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/twitter-reacts-to-kid-cudis-passion-pain-and-demon-slayin-album-release-news.26414.html|title=Twitter Reacts To Kid Cudi's "Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin" Album Release|work=hotnewhiphop.com|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepopbreak.com/2016/12/29/album-review-kid-cudi-passion-pain-demon-slayin/|title=Album Review: Kid Cudi, 'Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin'|first=Dylan|last=Brandsema|date=December 29, 2016|work=thepopbreak.com|accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref> Throughout the years he has also incorporated elements of [[Psychedelic music|psychedelia]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[electronica]], [[synthpop]] and [[grunge]], in his music.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lyons |first=Patrick |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/indie-cud-a-timeline-of-kid-cudi-s-indie-collabs-and-samples-news.14220.html |title=Indie-Cud: A Timeline Of Kid Cudi's Indie Collabs & Samples |website=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=March 4, 2015 |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name="hiphopdx.com">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/interviews/id.1408/title.kid-cudi-the-dark-side-of-the-moon|title=- HipHopDX|author=|date=September 16, 2009|work=HipHopDX}}</ref>

